notesStmt.note: Title from colophon and added title (f. 1r).

Catalog entry, number 580, pasted onto last flyleaf verso. A note in pencil "'Wonder Book' MS. Indian workmanship written in the Persian language XVIII cent. AD. Lahore, India" and the code $U1.II written onto last flyleaf recto at the back of the book.

msContents.summary: Copy of ʻAjāʼib al-makhlūqāt in Persian with diagrams and many color illustrations showing constellations, animals, plants, creatures and other wonders; the Arabic in the text is overlined in red.
msContents.textLang: Persian with some quotations in Arabic

author.name: Free Library of Philadelphia. Rare Book Department. John Frederick Lewis Collection of Oriental Manuscripts

supportDesc.extent: 292, i leaves : 263 x 160 (180 x 100) mm bound to 265 x 165 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in red ink, upper left recto by corner of the textbox; occasional separate catchword on verso, lower left, more often, the last word of the page is repeated at the top of the next page.

layoutDesc.layout: 23 long lines; border-ruled; catchwords in the bottom left of the textblock; marginal headings.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq in black ink; pointed.

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated headpiece in gold, blue, red and pink (f. 1v); numerous color illustrations, some full page, some half page and some smaller; diagrams in red and black (f. 9v, 10v-11v, 13r-14r, 15r, 16v, 204v-205v). Tables in red and black (f. 202r-202v, 213v-214v).Textblock is border-ruled in blue and double red; page-opening is frame ruled in blue. Rubrications in red, including marginal headings and overlining.
Description of the manuscript in pencil

binding.p: Bound in repaired dark red leather over pasteboard (Type III) with frame of green and yellow rules; doublure of plain paper with painted blue frame and tall, narrow window designs.

origin.p: Copy completed on 4 Jumādá al-Ulá 1243 (23 November 1827), the scribe's name has been scratched out, but is still somewhat legible and ends with the name Murād Bakhsh (f. 292r).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Oliver Henry Perkins (bookplate inside front cover).
Formerly owned by John Frederick Lewis.
